#Press Model: Use the 3 variable model
PRESS <- function(Linear_Model) {
    pr <- residuals(Linear_Model)/(1 - lm.influence(Linear_Model)$hat)
    sum(pr^2)
}

#B 
plot(tree_regression)

Based on the plots above, it is safe to assume that most of the regression assumptions are violated. The residuals vs fitted plot for the trees data has a bell curve. Bell curves are an indicator of abnormality in the dataset because residual vs fitted plots are supposed to have homoskedacity. The QQ Plot for the trees data depicts that most of the points are close in proximity to a dashed line. This means that the data is normally distributed, at least for the most part. Like the residuals vs fitted plot, the scale-location plot also lacks homoskedacity. This is an indicator of abnormality in how residuals are spread along the ranges of input variables. The residuals vs leverage plot suggests that there is a major outlier in the data set because there is a point with a 31 outside the 0.5 Cooks distance line.

##Project

#Overview

For my final project, I propose using the data I collected from a project I didnt get to complete last semester. The topic of my final project pertains to the issues of polarization and media bias detection. Over the course of the 2010s the issue of polarization increased in prevalence as access to smartphones increased in prevalence due to how social media algorithms personalize news feeds. The purpose of my project is to look for insights about how people consume and perceive their news feeds and gain an understanding of how polarization manifests.

#Research Questions

Q1: Do people judge news reliability based on which news station is broadcasting the content or on whether theyre hearing what they want to hear?

Q2: Does college education increase or decrease polarization?

#Hypotheses

H1: People care the most about hearing whether theyre hearing what they want to hear in their news than they do about who theyre hearing their news from.

H2: College-educated people will have less polarized results than non-college educated people.

#Experiment

For my experiment, I had my subjects read one of four possible news articles about presidential approval ratings. The titles of the articles were CNN Poll: Joe Bidens Approval Ratings Continue To Sink, CNN Poll: Donald Trumps Approval Ratings Continue To Sink, FOX News: Joe Bidens Approval Ratings Continue To Sink, and FOX News: Donald Trumps Approval Ratings Continue To Sink. After skimming the article, the subjects were asked How reliable is this source? and How well does this source cover all sides?. The questions were asked in a random order, but in the dataset from the survey, the order in which the subjects answered the questions was not indicated

#Operationalization

For question responses, the scale for each question was 0-10, with zero indicating that the source is unreliable and ten indicating that the source is reliable. For the sake of quantitative analysis, I also decided to assign a quantitative scale to the subjects political party. Symbolic of liberal being the left and conservative being the right, I assigned -3 to strongly liberal subjects, -2 to liberal subjects, -1 to independents with liberal leanings, 0 to independents without leanings, 1 to independents with conservative leanings, 2 to conservative subjects, and 3 to strongly conservative subjects.

##Data Cleaning
Project <- read.csv("/Users/rhyslong/Desktop/Project_Dataset.csv") %>%

         "Democrat"=Q18.10,
         "Closer_To"=Q18.11,
         "Election"=Q18.12) %>%
  slice(2:209) %>%
  arrange(Question_1) %>%
  arrange(Question_2) %>%
  slice(6:208) %>%
  mutate(Republican=case_when(
    Republican=="Not very strong Republican"~"Not_Strong",
    Republican=="Strong Republican"~"Strong",
  )) %>%
  mutate(Democrat=case_when(
    Democrat=="Not very strong Democrat"~"Not_Strong",
    Democrat=="Strong Democrat"~"Strong",
  )) %>%
  mutate(Closer_To=case_when(
    Closer_To=="Democrat"~"Leaning_Democrat",
    Closer_To=="Republican"~"Leaning_Republican",
  )) %>%
  unite("Specifics", Republican:Democrat, remove = TRUE) %>%
  unite("Specifics", Specifics:Closer_To, remove = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(Specifics=case_when(
    Specifics=="NA_NA_Leaning_Democrat" ~ "Leaning_Democrat",
    Specifics=="NA_NA_Leaning_Republican"~"Leaning_Republican",
    Specifics=="NA_Strong_NA"~"Strong",
    Specifics=="Strong_NA_NA"~"Strong",
  )) %>%
  unite("Specific_Party", Party:Specifics, remove = FALSE) %>%
  mutate(Party=case_when(
    Specific_Party=="Democrat_Strong" ~ -3,
    Specific_Party=="Democrat_NA" ~ -2,
    Specific_Party=="Independent_Leaning_Democrat" ~ -1,
    Specific_Party=="Independent_NA" ~ 0,
    Specific_Party=="Other_NA" ~ 0,
    Specific_Party== "No Preference_NA" ~ 0,
    Specific_Party=="Independent_Leaning_Republican"~ 1,
    Specific_Party=="Republican_NA" ~ 2,
    Specific_Party=="Republican_Strong"~3,
  )) %>%
  mutate(Black=case_when(
    Black=="African American or Black"~TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(Indigenous_American_or_Alaskan_Native=case_when(
    Indigenous_American_or_Alaskan_Native=="American Indian or Alaska Native"~TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(Asian=case_when(
    Asian=="Asian"~TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(Hispanic_or_Latino=case_when(
    Hispanic_or_Latino=="Hispanic or Latino"~TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(Middle_Eastern=case_when(
    Middle_Eastern=="Middle Eastern"~TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(White=case_when(
    White=="White"~TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(West_Indian=case_when(
    West_Indian=="Other"~TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(No_Disclosure=case_when(
    No_Disclosure=="Prefer not to answer"~TRUE)) %>%
  pivot_longer(Black:No_Disclosure, names_to = "Race", values_to = "Remove") %>%
  filter(Remove==TRUE) %>%
  select(Question_1:Race)%>%
  mutate(Question_1=case_when(
    Question_1 == "0: Highly Unreliable" ~ 0,
    Question_1 == "1" ~ 1,
    Question_1 == "2" ~ 2,
    Question_1 == "3" ~ 3,
    Question_1 == "4" ~ 4,
    Question_1 == "5: Neither Reliable or Unreliable" ~ 5,
    Question_1 == "6" ~ 6,
    Question_1 == "7" ~ 7,
    Question_1 == "8" ~ 8,
    Question_1 == "9" ~ 9,
    Question_1 == "10: Highly Reliable" ~ 10,
  )) %>%
  mutate(Question_2=case_when(
    Question_2 == "0: Not Well At All" ~ 0,
    Question_2 == "1" ~ 1,
    Question_2 == "2" ~ 2,
    Question_2 == "3" ~ 3,
    Question_2 == "4" ~ 4,
    Question_2 == "5: Moderately Well" ~ 5,
    Question_2 == "6" ~ 6,
    Question_2 == "7" ~ 7,
    Question_2 == "8" ~ 8,
    Question_2 == "9" ~ 9,
    Question_2 == "10: Extremely Well" ~ 10,
  )) %>%
  unite("President_Criticized", PresidentFirst:PresidentLast) %>%
  mutate(President_Criticized=case_when(
    President_Criticized=="Joe_Biden"~"Biden",
    President_Criticized=="Donald_Trump"~"Trump",
  )) %>%
  rename("News_Source"=NewsOrg) %>%
  unite("Article", News_Source:President_Criticized, remove = FALSE) %>%
  mutate(Specifics=case_when(
    Specifics == NA ~ "Regular",
    Specifics == "Strong"~"Strong",
    Specifics == "Leaning_Democrat"~"Leaning_Democrat",
    Specifics == "Leaning_Republican"~"Leaning_Republican",
  )) %>%
  pivot_longer(Question_1:Question_2, names_to = "Question", values_to = "Response") %>%
  mutate(Question=case_when(
    Question=="Question_1"~1,
    Question=="Question_2"~2,
  )) %>%
  mutate(Education=case_when(
    Education=="Associate's Degree"~"Undergraduate",
    Education=="Bachelor's Degree"~"Undergraduate",
    Education=="High School"~"High School",
    Education=="High School (Not Completed)"~"High School",
    Education=="Master's or PhD"~"Graduate",
    Education=="Some College coursework"~"Undergraduate",
  ))%>%
  select(Article:News_Source, Education, Party, Question, Response)

The fact that the first slope is negative suggests that liberal subjects perceive the source as more reliable than conservative subjects and the fact that the second slope is positive suggests that college educated people are more likely to perceive the source as reliable than subjects without college education. Moreover, the p-score for the college education slope is statistically significant, suggesting that college education does have an impact on perceptions of media bias.

ggplot(Data, aes(x=Party, y=Response, color=College))+geom_point()+geom_smooth(method="lm")+facet_wrap(vars(Article))

In the visuals above, the line for college educated subjects is consistently less steep than the line for subjects without a college education. This suggests not only that college education decreases polarization, but also that college educated people are less likely to judge news reliability on whether theyre hearing what they want to hear.
